.TH SLACKER 8 "June 2026" "slacker 0.4.0" "Slackware Package Management"
.SH NAME
slacker \- minimal package manager for Slackware (slackpkg + slackpkg+ in one)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B slacker
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.I COMMAND
.RI [ ARGS ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B slacker
manages Slackware packages over the network, combining the behaviour of
.BR slackpkg (8)
with the multi\-repository support of slackpkg+. It is a thin layer over the
native Slackware package tools: it never reimplements
.BR installpkg (8),
.BR upgradepkg (8)
or
.BR removepkg (8),
but resolves packages across one or more repositories and calls those tools to
make changes.
.PP
Every configured repository \(em the official Slackware mirror and any external
(slackpkg+\-style) repositories alike \(em is held in a single priority\-ordered
model. When the same package name is offered by several repositories, the one
from the highest\-priority repository wins. A specific repository can be forced
with the
.I repo:package
syntax.
.PP
.B slacker
resolves dependencies from per\-package
.I .dep
files when a repository provides them, pulling in any missing dependencies from
the same repository before installing. This is on by default and can be turned
off globally with
.B RESOLVE_DEPS=no
or per run with
.BR \-\-no\-deps " (see " DEPENDENCIES ")."
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-config\-dir " DIR"
Directory holding the plain\-text configuration files. Default
.IR /etc/slacker .
.TP
.BR \-y ", " \-\-yes
Assume "yes" to confirmation prompts.
.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run
Show what would happen without changing the system.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-deps
Do not read
.I .dep
files or pull in dependencies for this run.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print help and exit.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print version and exit.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Metadata
.TP
.B update \fR[\fBgpg\fR]
First checks every active repository for changes (cheaply: the official repo by
its ChangeLog, the others by comparing CHECKSUMS.md5) and prints a status table.
If nothing has changed it stops with \fIAll up\-to\-date\fR and touches nothing.
Otherwise it lists the repositories that have updates and lets you refresh all
of them, a chosen subset (by number), or none. Only the repositories you pick
are downloaded; the rest \(em including their cached MANIFEST \(em are left
untouched. The form
.B update gpg
downloads and imports each repository's GPG key into a private keyring, and
should be run once before the first
.BR update .
.TP
.B check-updates
Check every configured repository for pending updates since the last update, one
status line per repo. The official repo is checked via its ChangeLog; external
repos by comparing CHECKSUMS.md5 against the cached copy. Exits 100 if any repo
has updates pending.
.TP
.B show-changelog
Print the cached ChangeLog.
.SS Querying
.TP
.BI search " NAME"
Find a package by its exact name (case-insensitive), across all repositories,
showing the candidate from the highest-priority repo. Unlike
.BR file-search ,
this does not substring-match: \fIfoo\fR matches only \fIfoo\fR, not
\fIlibfoo\fR or \fIfoobar\fR.
.TP
.BI file-search " FILENAME"
Report which package ships a given file, using the repository MANIFEST. The
MANIFEST is downloaded on first use and can be large.
.TP
.BI info " PACKAGE"
Show the installed version and the available candidates per repository
(highest priority first), with sizes and description.
.SS Installing and removing
.TP
.BI install " PATTERN..."
Install new packages. Already\-installed packages are refused (use
.B upgrade
or
.B reinstall
instead).
.TP
.BI upgrade " PATTERN..."
Upgrade installed packages to the newest available revision.
.TP
.BI reinstall " PATTERN..."
Reinstall the currently installed version.
.TP
.BI remove " PATTERN..."
Remove installed packages.
.TP
.BI download " PATTERN..."
Download package files without installing them. By default they are saved under
.IR CACHE_DIR/packages/<repo>/ ,
the same place install uses, so a later install reuses them. Pass
.B \-o
.I DIR
(or
.BR \-\-output )
to save elsewhere, e.g.
.I /tmp
or the current directory. Selecting a whole repo or tag (e.g.
.IR @alienbob )
asks for confirmation when more than ten packages would be downloaded.
.SS Bulk operations
.TP
.B upgrade-all
Upgrade every installed package that has a newer revision available.
.TP
.B install-new
Install packages whose name is newly added since the last update \(em a package
that did not exist before, not merely a new build or version of one that already
existed (that is an upgrade). By default only the official repo(s); name one or
more repositories to use those instead.
.TP
.B clean-system
List installed packages that exist in no configured repository (third\-party or
removed packages) in a numbered table, then let you choose which to remove: type
numbers to keep, press Enter to remove all, or cancel. Blacklisted packages, and packages
whose build tag is listed in
.B IGNORE_TAGS
(SBo source builds, your own builds, etc.), are never listed or removed. With
.B \-\-yes
all listed packages are removed.
.TP
.B clean-cache \fR[\fIREPO\fR...]
Delete downloaded package files from
.IR CACHE_DIR/packages .
Repo metadata and GPG keys (under
.IR CACHE_DIR/repos )
are never touched. Limit to named repos, or clean every repo. Asks before
deleting and reports how much space is freed.
.TP
.B new-config
Reconcile leftover \fI*.new\fR configuration files under /etc and
/usr/share/vim. For each one a coloured unified diff against the installed file
is shown, then you choose to (K)eep both files unchanged and decide later
(the default, nothing is deleted), (O)verwrite the installed file with the
\fI.new\fR, (R)emove just the \fI.new\fR and keep your current file, (M)erge the
two with an external tool, or (D)iff again. A \fI.new\fR byte-identical to the
installed file is removed automatically. The merge tool is
.B vimdiff
by default and may be overridden with the
.B SLACKER_MERGE
environment variable. After
.B upgrade-all
any pending \fI.new\fR files \(em both newly installed and pre-existing \(em are
listed with a reminder to run this command.
.SS Templates
.TP
.BI generate-template " NAME"
Snapshot the installed package set into a template.
.TP
.BI install-template " NAME"
Install every package listed in a template (following includes).
.TP
.BI remove-template " NAME"
Uninstall every package listed in a template (removes packages from the system;
to delete only the template file use
.BR delete-template ).
.TP
.BI delete-template " NAME"
Delete a template file. Installed packages are not touched.
.TP
.BI frozen " NAME..."
Add one or more packages to the blacklist, freezing them so that update,
upgrade-all, reinstall, and clean-system leave them alone.
.SH PRIVILEGES
Read-only commands
.RB ( search ", " info ", " file-search ", " check-updates ", " show-changelog )
run as any user. Commands that change the system, the cache, or the
configuration (everything else) must be run as root; non-root invocations stop
with a clear message before doing anything.
.PP
Those same commands take an exclusive lock
.RI ( /run/slacker.lock )
so only one runs at a time; a second one exits immediately reporting the running
PID. The lock is held by the kernel and released automatically if slacker exits,
crashes, or is killed, so it never gets stuck. Queries take no lock and run
freely in parallel.
.SH PATTERNS
A
.I PATTERN
may be an exact package name, a substring of a package name, a Slackware series
name
.RB ( a ", " ap ", " d ", " k ", " kde ", " l ", " n ", " t ", " x ", " xap ", " xfce ", " y ", " ...),
or a
.I repo:name
pin that forces a specific repository regardless of priority.
.PP
Two explicit set selectors are also accepted (the @ is required, so a bare word
is never treated as a repo):
.TP
.BI @ repo
For
.B install
and
.BR download ,
every package available in that repo, e.g.
.I @gnome
to install a whole desktop repo. For commands acting on installed packages
.RB ( upgrade ", " reinstall ", " remove )
it means every installed package whose build tag belongs to that repo \(em the
packages actually built from it \(em so a same\-named package installed from
another source is left untouched.
.TP
.BI @ _tag
Every package carrying that build tag, e.g.
.I @_SBo
to remove all installed SlackBuilds.org packages.
.SH FILES
All configuration is plain text under
.I /etc/slacker
(overridable with
.BR \-\-config\-dir ).
.TP
.I /etc/slacker/slacker.conf
Global settings as
.IR KEY=value .
.B ARCH
is auto\-detected from the installed
.I aaa_base
package and need only be set to force a specific architecture.
.B CACHE_DIR
(default
.IR /var/cache/slacker )
holds downloaded metadata and packages.
.B PKG_DB_DIR
(default
.IR /var/lib/pkgtools/packages )
is the installed\-package database.
.B VERIFY
(default
.IR all )
sets the package verification policy.
With
.IR all ,
a GPG signature is verified when present (a bad signature always fails), and at
least one integrity checksum (md5 or sha) must be present and match; if neither
md5 nor sha is available, installation stops. A comma list such as
.I gpg,md5,sha
REQUIRES those methods: if one is absent slacker stops and explains how to relax
it.
.I none
disables verification. Override per repo with a
.I verify=
flag on the repos line \(em useful when a repo ships a broken or missing
checksum or signature.
.TP
.B RESOLVE_DEPS
(default
.IR yes )
controls whether
.I .dep
files are read to pull in dependencies.
.B IGNORE_TAGS
is a space\-separated list of build tags (e.g.
.IR "_SBo cf alien" )
that
.B clean-system
must not treat as foreign \(em for packages from sources not managed as binary
repositories.
.PP
The
.I repos
file may also contain
.B build\-tag priority
lines of the form
.IR "priority name tag" ,
where the third field is a build tag rather than a URL (e.g.
.IR "100 SBo _SBo" ).
These assign a priority to packages built from non\-binary sources
(SlackBuilds.org, local builds).
.BR upgrade ", " reinstall " and " upgrade-all
only replace such a package with a candidate from a repository of higher or
equal priority, so tagged packages are never silently migrated to a lower repo
or downgraded. Only an explicit
.I repo:name
pin overrides this and forces the chosen repository's build.
.PP
When an
.BR install ,
.BR upgrade ,
or
.B reinstall
pattern matches more than one package, slacker prints a numbered list and lets
you choose which to act on (Enter for all, numbers or ranges such as
.I 1 3 5
or
.IR 2-4 ,
or
.I n
to cancel). A series name (a, ap, kde, y, ...) matches exactly that series
rather than every package whose name contains those letters.
.TP
.I /etc/slacker/mirrors
Catalogue of official Slackware mirrors. Exactly one line must be uncommented;
.B slacker
errors out if two are active. Supports
.IR http:// ", " https:// " and " file:// "."
.TP
.I /etc/slacker/repos
Repository priorities, names and external repositories, one per line as
.IR "priority name url" " [" official "]."
Higher priority wins. The official line's URL is the keyword
.B mirror
which is filled in from the active line in
.IR mirrors .
.TP
.I /etc/slacker/blacklist
Package names that must never be installed, upgraded or removed, one per line.
.TP
.I /etc/slacker/templates/
Generated and user\-created template files.
.SH DEPENDENCIES
When a package in a repository is accompanied by a
.I .dep
file (sharing the package's name with a
.I .dep
extension), each line of that file names a dependency package.
.B slacker
reads it and, before installing the package, pulls in any missing dependencies
from the
.I same
repository, recursively. Dependencies already satisfied by the same
repository's build are left alone. A dependency that is installed but differs
from what the repository offers (for example installed from another source)
triggers a prompt:
.IR skip ", " replace ", " skip\-all " or " abort .
With
.B \-\-yes
the installed version is kept. The whole mechanism is on by default and can be
disabled with
.B RESOLVE_DEPS=no
or, per run, with
.BR \-\-no\-deps .
This applies to every command that installs packages
.RB ( install ", " upgrade ", " reinstall ", " upgrade-all ", " install-new ", "
.BR install-template ).
.SH SECURITY
When a repository GPG key has been imported with
.BR "update gpg" ,
.B slacker
verifies CHECKSUMS.md5 against its detached signature on every
.BR update .
If that signature is bad or its key is missing, the repository is not aborted
wholesale: slacker warns, discards that repo's freshly\-fetched metadata so it
is never used unverified, and continues with the other repositories. It then
tells you how to proceed if you trust the repo anyway (relax its
.I verify=
in the repos file, or import its key) and re\-run.
.PP
Before installation each package is checked according to the repo's policy: its
md5 (and sha when provided) from the signature\-verified CHECKSUMS, and \(em when
the policy includes gpg \(em its own detached
.I .txz.asc
signature, which most Slackware repositories ship per package. A bad per\-package
signature is fatal. Under
.I all
a missing per\-package signature falls back to the checksum; under an explicit
.I gpg
it is required.
.PP
If any active repository ends up with no verification at all (global
.B VERIFY=none
with no per\-repo override, or an explicit
.IR verify=none ),
.B slacker
prints a warning after
.B update
and in
.B check-updates
naming those repositories. This applies to
.I file://
repositories as well.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred.
.TP
.B 20
No package was found to act on.
.TP
.B 50
.B slacker
upgraded itself and must be re\-run.
.TP
.B 100
There are pending updates (from
.BR check-updates ).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B SLACKER_MERGE
External merge tool invoked by
.B new-config
for the (M)erge action, called as \fItool installed-file file.new\fR. Defaults
to
.BR vimdiff .
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
When set (to any value), all coloured output is disabled. Colour is also
suppressed automatically when standard output is not a terminal.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
First\-time setup: choose a mirror in
.IR /etc/slacker/mirrors ,
then:
.PP
.RS
.nf
slacker update gpg
slacker update
.fi
.RE
.PP
Find and install a package:
.PP
.RS
.nf
slacker search firefox
slacker install mozilla-firefox
.fi
.RE
.PP
Force a package from a specific repository:
.PP
.RS
.nf
slacker install alienbob:vlc
.fi
.RE
.PP
Upgrade the whole system:
.PP
.RS
.nf
slacker update
slacker install-new
slacker upgrade-all
slacker clean-system
.fi
.RE
